THE Ndwedwe Municipality and police have launched an investigation into a fire that destroyed four municipal vehicles yesterday. Mayor Vincent Chili told Daily Sun he received a call from security guards in the morning informing him the municipality’s head offices were on fire. READ: MFR SOULS IN SCARY ACCIDENT! The mayor said the guards had told him the fire started in the early hours of the morning. They didn’t know the cause and no break-in had been detected. “We’re shocked and disturbed by the incident, but we don’t want to speculate about the cause of the fire”, he said. “We have reported the matter to the police and we will also do our own investigation. “We’re concerned this could prevent us from providing services.” He said two bakkies were completely destroyed while two others were damaged.  Chili said according to the guards’ report, they were the first to notice the smoke in the parking lot. The bakkies were on fire and they called firefighters, who were able to put out the fire before it spread to other buildings and cars. READ: ZUMA VISITS CAPITEC BRANCH WITH DUDU MYENI Chili said the incident was a blow to the municipality as scores of people left homeless by a storm over Christmas still needed help. KZN police spokeswoman Captain Nqobile Gwala said the matter was reported but no case had been opened yet.